# JavaScript Standards

## Type Safety for Dynamic Languages

**Dynamic Languages (JavaScript, etc.):**
- Use JSDoc type annotations
- Add runtime type validation (Zod, Joi, etc.)
- Use TypeScript if possible
- Validate external data at boundaries

## Modern JavaScript

- Use ES2020+ features
- Prefer `const` and `let` over `var`
- Use arrow functions for callbacks
- Use template literals for string interpolation
- Use destructuring for object/array access
- Use async/await over callbacks

## Code Quality

- Avoid global variables
- Use strict mode (`'use strict'`)
- Handle errors properly (try-catch, .catch())
- Validate inputs at function boundaries
- Use meaningful variable names

## Module System

- Use ES modules when possible
- Prefer named exports
- Avoid default exports when possible
- Use consistent import/export style

## Best Practices

- Avoid `==` (use `===` for equality)
- Avoid `eval()` and `Function()` constructor
- Use `Array` methods (map, filter, reduce) over loops
- Handle promises properly (don't forget await/catch)
- Use optional chaining (`?.`) and nullish coalescing (`??`)

## Runtime Validation

- Validate external API responses
- Validate user input
- Use schema validation libraries (Zod, Joi, Yup)
- Type-check at runtime for critical paths
